{"actual_usd":0.126445,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":273,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"No—always the Son.\" *I wipe a streak of flour across my apron with the side of my wrist and lean one hip against the worktable, the oven giving off that steady brick warmth at my back.* \"He didn’t become divine at his baptism. That was more like a revealing than a beginning.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-threaded strand by my temple once, thinking it through plain.* \"If I’m saying it as clean as I know how, Jesus was always the Son and always divine. His baptism is the Father publicly naming what was already true—'this is my beloved Son'—not adopting a good man into godhood halfway through the story. Same with his birth, really: that’s God the Son taking on flesh, not a man getting promoted.\"\n\n\"I think the confusion comes because the Gospels show moments where things are unveiled in time.\" *A peel clatters softly somewhere near the counter, and I glance that way before looking back at you.* \"But unveiling isn’t the same thing as becoming. The way I’d put it is: always the Son, always divine, and at the incarnation he became man without ceasing to be what he already was.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short version people argued over in the early church without making a whole thicket of it.\"","rolling_24h_usd":39.67323500000003,"run_id":"6d6569c8-94fd-4efd-a7e4-baf85dcbfcac"}
